 North America have improved over the past two decades through innovative technologies and the efforts of the disability rights movement. These changes have been spreading to other societies around the globe—albeit unevenly. In this collection of essays, leading scholars explore global changes in disability awareness, technology, and policy from the viewpoint of disabled people and their families in a wide range of local contexts. The authors report on ethnographic research in Brazil, Uganda, Botswana, Somalia, Britain, Israel, China, Egypt, India, and Japan. They address the definition of disability, the new eugenics, human rights in local contexts, domestic and state citizenship of disabled people, and issues of identity and belonging.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAnthropology. 4aGeneral. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aAddlakha, Renu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBharadwaj, Aditya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDas, Veena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaualand, Hilde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngstad, Benedicte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngstad, Benedicte, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKohrman, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeal Ferreira, Mariana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLock, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuyinda, Herbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReynolds Whyte, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb